'''Ahmad Ibrahim al-Sayyid al-Naggar''' was a member of [[Egyptian Islamic Jihad]]. The Jewish lobby group [[Anti-Defamation Group|ADL]] dubbed him the "propaganda chief" of the militant organisation.<ref>[[Anti-Defamation League]], [http://www.adl.org/Terror/focus/15_focus.asp US EMbassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania], Autumn 1998</ref> He was one of 14 people subjected to [[extraordinary rendition]] by the [[CIA]] prior to the 2001 declaration of a [[War on Terror]].<ref>[[Mother Jones]], [http://motherjones.com/politics/2008/03/disappearing-act-rendition-numbers Disappearin Act: Rendition by the Numbers], March 3, 2008</ref>

==Life==
His permanent address was on al-Shaikh al-Husari street in [[Giza]].<ref name="berg">Bergen, Peter. "The Osama bin Laden I Know", 2006</ref>

In 1994, he was asked to travel to Sudan, and was subsequently introduced to [[Ayman al-Zawahiri]], who asked him to oversee civil organisation of [[al-Jihad]].<ref name="berg"/> 

In October of the following year, Zawahiri asked him to instead travel to Yemen to oversee civil operations there; but three months later was told to travel with his fake passport in the name of ''Ahmed Rajab Mohammed'', to take a job as a teacher with the [[Haramain|Haramain charity]] in [[Tirana, Albania]].<ref name="berg"/> He also led the ''Centre for Islamic Heritage''.<ref name="Military trial for bombing suspects">[[al-Ahram]], [http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/1998/402/eg7.htm Military trial for bombing suspects], November 5<U+2013>11, 1998</ref>

==Capture, trials, execution==
{{rquote|right|Osama wanted to launch a guerrilla war not only in the Arab and Islamic world, but in the whole world...he believed these attacks would force America and its allies to change their policy in the Middle East and the Islamic world|al-Naggar, during trial<ref>Sachs, Susan. [[New York Times]], "An Investigation in Egypt Illustrates Al Qaeda's Web", November 21, 2001</ref>}}
He was sentenced in death [[in absentia]] in an Egyptian military court on October 15, 1997 for the crime of membership in al-Jihad, and possession of weapons.<ref name="berg"/><ref name="amnesty"/><ref name="hrw">[[Human Rights Watch]], [http://www.hrw.org/en/node/11757/section/6 Black Hole: The 1995 and 1998 Renditions]</ref> He was ostensibly linked to the 1995 plot to blow up the [[Khan el-Khalili|Khan el-Khalili market]], as well as the the assassination of Speaker of Parliament [[Rifaat el-Mahgoub]] in October 1990.<ref name="vic">[[Victoria Advocate]], [http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3TIKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EEsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6853,2521016&dq=khan+el+khalili+market&hl=en Bombings connect to mysterious arrests], August 13, 1998</ref><ref name="Military trial for bombing suspects"/><ref>24ur.com, [http://24ur.com/novice/svet/islamski-skrajnezi-napovedali-nove-protiameriske-napade.html Islamski skrajne<U+017E>i napovedali nove protiameri<U+0161>ke napade], February 4, 1999</ref> The trial was condemned as "unfair" by [[Amnesty International]].<ref name="amnesty">[[Amnesty International]], [http://www-secure.amnesty.org/fr/library/asset/MDE12/005/2000/fr/13e6f536-df7a-11dd-8abb-118b2e919ec0/mde120052000en.html Ahmed Ibrahim al-Naggar], February 29, 2000</ref> 

In 1998, Bary asked al-Naggar to claim asylum in the [[United Kingdom]], so he could help convince [[Hani Sibai]] to support the Algerian [[GIA]] in media communiques.<ref>Pargeter, Alison. "The New Frontiers of Jihad", p. 54</ref>

He was arrested on July 2, 1998 as he stepped off the plane in Cairo, having been deported from Albania with the help of the [[CIA]].<ref name="berg"/> His wife was also arrested, and interrogated for three days during which time she was subjected to [[electrical torture]].

He was tried in the 1999 [[Returnees from Albania]] trial at which he was defended by [[Montasser el-Zayat]]. He was tortured for nine months; locked in a room with water up to his knees 24 hours a day. When taken to [[SSI]] headquarters in [[Lazughli Square]] and questioned by Captain Yasir Azzulddin,<ref name="berg"/> his hands and feet were tied, as interrogators applied electric shocks to his nipples and penis.<ref name="hrw"/><ref>Duthel, Heinz. "The Bilderberger Group - Saviors or Destroyers?", p. 271</ref> 

Under torture, al-Naggar admitted that al-Jihad had acquired [[anthrax]] from an unnamed East Asian country for $3,695.<ref>Begley, Sharon. [[Newsweek]], "The history of weaponized anthrax suggests that investigators have no shortage of suspects in the new bio-attacks"</ref> He also admitted that EIJ raised money by raising sheep, and "renovating old houses" in [[London, England]].<ref>Infowars.com, [http://www.infowars.com/saved%20pages/Prior_Knowledge/10_years_cell.htm Bin Laden had US terror cell for a decade], November 11, 2001</ref> He later claimed his confessions were only a result of this torture. He was sentenced to 25 years' imprisonment.<ref name="hrw"/> In November, he was transferred to Tora prison, where Amnesty noted he was at less risk of torture or sudden execution.<ref name="pdf">[[Amnesty International]], [http://www.amnesty.org/en/library/asset/MDE12/052/1998/en/19bceadf-f87b-11dd-a0a9-2bd73ca4d38a/mde120521998en.pdf Further information], November 12, 1998</ref>

Together with the other three Returnees brought from Tirana, his capture and torture were listed as the main reasons for the [[1998 United States embassy bombings]].<ref name="vic"/>

He was hanged on February 23, 2000 at al-Isti<U+2019>naf prison, due to the earlier death sentence levied against him.<ref name="amnesty"/><ref name="hrw"/>

